mainfeelexpl: I feel sad because it is a very sad story. For someone to miss their best friend's bachelorette party is pretty sad.  I feel empathy because i feel sorry for this girl.  And I am surprised because why would she let someone who had car trouble very short before her trip let her drive here there?
I feel bad for the person writing the letter. Because of her friend; she was unable to attend a party she planned and was looking forward to.

I was interested to hear about the bacherlorette party (I am only 19 so I haven't had an opportunity to attend an event similar to this). Yet disappointed for her. It is sad to hear about all of the planning she had done; and I'm sure the writer was very excited to see her best friend. It is a shame that she was not able to.

Reading the letter feels as if what was written was specifically shared with me. A letter gives the impression of greater sincerity; as it is in the authors own writing. What was written takes on a greater importance as a result. Because of sincerity that letters have; I feel included; which allows myself to feel comfort and calm.
I feel bad for the girl's struggle in the letter I read and the unfortunate situation she was put in because she was lied to.
I felt sorry for Melissa because she missed her bestfriends bachelorette party. I was angry because the guy that offered to take them lied about get his car fixed and the car ended up breaking down.

I felt sadness and empathy for the girl; Melissa; who wrote the letter because she described a sad event where she was unable to visit her best friend for her bachelorette party and how she cried because of this. That made me feel sad for her.
I feel bad for the author because I can't imagine being in her shoes
I don't really feel anything out of the ordinary right now.
I would be so devastated if I missed my best friend's Bachelorette party; therefore; I feel sorry and upset that it happened to Melissa.
I feel the same way that I did walking in to this expirement.

The writer merely described a common experience that; quite frankly; is portrayed in many films. I understand that what this writer felt may have been quite troublesome; however; it is nothing too signficant to dwell on.

I feel sympathetic for the writer; and also indignance at what her friend did.  However; I do feel like she should calm down a little bit; it sounded like she's been pouting for a while.  I feel astonished that someone would lie about something like taking the car to the mechanic.  Why not just tell the truth? What have you got to lose? Weird.
jealous that she has a good enough friend to come bring her back to ann arbor after being a quarter of the way to NYC

I feel bad that she was stuck with no other options to make it to New York for her friends party. I am annoyed that her friends car broke down and there was nothing they could do. Even though she could have come up with a back up plan earlier; her friend insisted he would have it all handled. I feel bad for him too because he unintentionally had the responsibility for the girls not making it there and had to feel guilty.

I was instructed to remain objective while reading the letter so the letter did not truly elicit any feelings from me. I'm a little suspicious because I have the feeling that the letter I was given was planned in order to get a specific response from me.

I feel sad that Melissa missed her best friend's bachelorette party due to a friend's car troubles. It is really unfortunate that the car was replaced with a defective part; and that was the reason that she couldn't make it to New York.
My cousin just recently got married so it's easy for me to imagine missing her bachelorette party and I would be feeling the same things as the girl who wrote the letter I read.

I feel sympathy towards the participant because she missed her best friend's bachelorette party; and I feel anger at her friend who lied about getting the car fixed thus causing her to miss her friends party.
The experience that the person had gone through was quite negative; and I feel horribly for the writer.

The letter started out by showing how excited and interested Melissa was in being able to take a road trip with one of her best friends. Then I began to feel very sorry for her that she was unable to make the trip because of circumstances out of her control.
The girls letter was pretty sad. Things just didn't go her way so I feel bad for her.
I am sad for Melissa
The letter did not create a lot of new feelings
She did nothing wrong; but as a result of her friend; she missed an event that she really wanted to go to.
I feel annoyed because she could have not been as cheap and just paid for a flight to begin with. If she was going to do that in the end she clearly could have afforded it.

I would feel betrayed that my friend lied to me. If you are a good friend; you wouldn't hurt me like that. I would also be hurt that I didn't get to go to my best friends bachelorette party. I would remember this for the rest of my life and never forgive the friend that lied to me about getting the repairs
I'm happy because I love weddings and her best friend is getting married; and I'm upset for the girl and her troubles.

I understand where the writer is coming from and I feel regretful and sympathetic towards the writer because of the situation that she was put in. I am also slightly annoyed because I can relate to her situation in that I have met many people who lie and are not straightforward about things. This often comes back to hurt them and also those around them and is something that bothers me a lot.
Mostly I feel sympathetic toward Melissa's experiences because I know that in that circumstance I would be upset as well; especially because it seemed that nothing worked out.

I felt very bad for the participant as she had missed a very important event with her longtime best friend and the whole plan failed because the trust that she put into her other friend had failed as well. I know that if someone made me miss something that important I would feel enraged at that person.

I feel bad for the girl because she missed her best friends bachelorette party; and I am thinking of ways that the situation could have been fixed/imagining different scenarios that could have played out had the car not broke down.
Sympathy with the author; anger at the friend; and disappointment at the story as a whole.

She wasn't able to make it to her best friend's bachelorette party because the car she was in broke down along the way. I can relate to this as I was in my best friend's wedding last year; and if I had missed the bachelorette party I would've been devastated; just like the past participant was. I wish I could've helped her get to New York; because I feel bad that this unfortunate event happened.
Ultimately my feeling is that of  fear of missing out. And anger for all the people who had let her down.
The events that happened to the writer are unfortunate; so those were my natural reactions to it.
I feel like this because the way she wrote about she felt was less prevalent to the story than the story itself and so the ending felt abrupt and it seemed less genuine in my opinion.

I would feel regretful that I decided to go with another friend who was having car troubles before; and that even though they were being nice and letting me go with them to NYC; I would be regretful of my decision to go with them on this trip. I would be sad I missed my best friends party that both of us had been looking forward to for such a long time - especially because it is in NYC. I would be frustrated in the end because of all of this and the way it worked out.
I can't believe that the writer's friend let her down like that. The friend was dishonest and it upsets me that her friend lied and it ended up in upsetting consequences for the writer.

It is upsetting that a friend of hers lied about a car getting repaired; and she had to miss her best friends bachelorette party. She included many details that made her story seem relatable. Such as her best friend of two years going to a city that they always wanted to go to; and how she couldn't spend a pivotal moment of her life with her.
I'm content with how I feel since I am supposed to be objective and detached. I do feel a little sad for Melissa but also happy my break went smoother.
I feel annoyed on the writer's behalf but since it does not affect me; I do not have any strong emotions towards it.
After reading this letter; I feel sorry for her because she described an unfortunate event that is very practical and could happen to anyone.

Overall; I feel sad for Melissa that she missed her friend's party.  I am also wondering if she has considered any other options she can take to make up for the circumstances that were out of her control.

I can feel Melissa's disappointment after reading her letter. She said that she is fuming about the situation; but I don't feel her anger. I feel sadness; regret and disappointment instead because that's how I usually feel when I miss opportunities.
Although the experience was not life-or-death; I would not want to be in her shoes and miss her best friend's bachelorette party.
I didn't find the story very interesting.

I certainly can understand the writer's letter  because I just went through a experience where a friend lied to my face.  I felt the same frustration that she felt by not wanting to talk to that person. And I was curious to why she just didn't take a plane in the first place. Why waste so much time driving?
The girl missed her best friends bachelorette party because her friends car broke down. It sad because she missed an event she was looking forward to.
Her letter was about an unfortunate event

I'm feeling sympathetic towards Melissa because she missed a monumental event in one of her best friend's lives that she can't re-do; and that must be really hard.  I feel frustrated because it's annoying that the guy would lie about getting his car fixed; and confused about why he lied about it because he got screwed over as well.

The girl in the letter explained how she had a horrible week  because she had to miss her best friend of 10 years  bacherlotte party. She wrote about how she tried her hardest and that on the drive there her rides engine died out and that she couldn't get a flight/.

I feel bad for Melissa and am appalled that her friend would do such a thing to her - I'm sad that she missed her bachelorette party. However; observing it from the standpoint like it's a fictional story; I find it to be slightly humorous.

It is a shame that Melissa wasn't able to make her best friend's bachelorette party; especially since it was due to a freaky series of events that boil down to bad luck. However; there could've been more tragic circumstances; all things considered.
Her personal experience was sad and frustrating because she was told a lie by her friend and because of her friend's lie she had to miss her best friend's bachelorette party
The letter writer was not able to attend her friends bachelorette party because of car troubles; and she was very disappointed about it.
just got out of class; and the story was not very interesting; so im not entertained.
Her story was sad and disappointing to read which made me feel this way inside. On top of that I was unsure what to write about at first and her story/ paragraph is much better than mine

It was intriguing and humorous to see this one girl's perspective on a series of events that resulted in her missing a bachelorette party (will consider using as evidence that women are crazy; just kidding).
I feel so badly that she missed the party. It is not fair that she had to deal with the consequences of a bad decision on her friends part.
her friend lied to her and let her down
I'm so sorry that something like that happened to her; I would be pissed too. I wonder why her friend would lie about getting the car serviced before a long distance road trip.

I feel sorry that melissa had to miss an event that she was so looking forward to. I also feel angry because her friend lied to her and lying is something i take very seriously and do not tolerate; which is why i feel sympathetic towards her based off of experiences i have had with friends lying.
Annoyance at the person the writer was talking about; not her.

My story also involved car trouble so I am surprised by this coincidence. I am disappointed that this person would be so upset with their friend who is doing them a favor; but I understand where they are coming from.

The participant's letter was about how she missed her best friend's bachelorette party when she wsa the maid of honor for teh friend's wedding. She was on her way to the party in New York City wehn the car she was in broke down and she had to go back to Ann Arbor. At the end the participant had said that she was "tearing up thinking about it now. I still can't believe that happened and I'm still really upset about it." So I feel sorry for this girl for not being able to participate in her best friend's bachelorette party even when she had planned it.
Just generally confused about the purpose of the study and why I am supposed to be reading the letters.
I feel bad for Melissa (this past participant); and angry for her at the guy who lied to her. I am surprised she couldn't find a flight to NY and surprised that the guy did not take the car in.
I feel sad that the girl did not get to make it to the party. I also feel surprised that her friend would lie about something so important.
The participant wrote about an experience that was interesting but sort of sucked for her. A series of unfortunate events.

Although I don't have any major connection with the participant; everybody has encountered a moment when nothing seems to go as planned.  The writer's note doesn't affect me personally in any way; but hearing of another person's struggle never makes me feel better about myself.
Was told to remain objective. So whether I feel happy or sad is irrelevant.

I was told to remain objective before reading this letter and it wasn't difficult to do because I do not know anything about this person I am emotionally detached from them. This letter being in writing also allowed me to remain emotionally detached because as a medium for expression you have to be a great writer to elicit strong feelings of any kind.
I think the participant had a bad experience but it's funny to see someone depend on a bad friend. /

I felt this emotions because this girl was so upset that her friend lied to her and then she missed her best friend's bachelorette party. Though I could push down my emotions a bit; I couldn't fully because it was very unfair for this girl to have to experience that.
I feel bad for Melissa; she had a big plan that was truly important to her and it ended up not happening. I bet she is really going to think about getting a  flight instead of a car from now on.
I feel bad for the girl; she missed out on her best friends bachelorette party because another one of her friends lied to her about getting his car fixed.

This person ended up missing her best friend's bachelorette party because of a friend's car trouble. Putting myself in that situation; I know how frustrated and upset I would be; not able to get to the party and being completely helpless to do anything about it.
I can relate to her experience of being let down by a close friend and missing a major part of another friend's wedding because I experienced something similar.

I could feel how disappointed and upset the past participant was;  but what happened to her was not a very great deal; I think she should try to understand why her friend lied to her; it's because her friend really wanted her to go with him; it is a reflection of friendship; as well.
I am upset and unhappy about the author who missed her best friend's wedding party. I am angry about the author's another friend.

I tried to be detached but I have a best friend too and I kept imagining myself in the same situation -- that I might have to miss her bachelorette party... I'd feel really really awful too. And the fact that she cried for a few days; I can really feel her.

The letter explains a situation where the person was lied to and it prevented her from going somewhere important with her best friend. This letter made me annoyed and a little angry that someone would lie like that. This letter also made me sympathetic towards the writer.

The story I read had more drama and disappointment than mine but both provoked anticipation. We were both in a tentative situation and since my emotions are still raw I move between my powerlessness and that of the writer; able to reflect on both situations.

I feel so sorry that this happened to this participant. When I first read the letter; I thought that would be an exciting story because she wanted to visit New York with her friends and she was actually going to her best friend's wedding. But there was something wrong with their car and they just couldn't make it to NY. She missed the trip and her best friend's wedding. It's just so sad...
The letter writer had really unfortunate luck. I would be more annoyed for her but I was told to be detached while reading it so I tried to push away that kind of strong emotion.
Tired because I've been working hard. Happy that I don't have the problems young people do. Eager to get back home to work.

It is a pity that the writer anticipated attending her best friend's bachelorette party in New York City; something they had hoped to do together for a long time; just to have her plans get screwed by a lazy jerk. I feel sympathetic regarding her loss of once-a-lifetime opportunity because of a liar.

I feel for Melissa that she was not able to attend her best friend's bachelorette party.  I also hate being lied to; so I can imagine how frustrated she was when her friend; her transportation to the bachelorette party in NYC; lied to her about getting his car fixed.  Not only did he waste her time and make her miss the party; but he also wasted his own.

The letter I read detailed a very unfortunate experience that a previous participant went through. While reading the letter; I empathized with this participant and honestly felt very badly for her because she experienced this.

The story I read was sad. Even from an objective point of view; hearing of this situation would be difficult to handle for any person. The distance would make it difficult for anyone to come back to Ann Arbor. Nothing in this situation seemed to be fair.
I thought that the situation was extremely unfortunate and the sadness that was felt was extremely avoidable if the correct knowledge was held.
The letter's pretty negative. Not very interesting though.

I think that it is really unfortunately that this happened to this individual; but I think her crying over it while writing the letter is a little overboard. I think she deserves to feel frustrated because she was trying to be responsible with the whole car ordeal; but at the end of the day; she still gets to be with her friend on her wedding day; the most important part in all this.
This story is so sad because if I were her; I would be so upset that I missed my best friends baccalaureate party (a once in a life time opportunity.)
what a pity about she missed the best friend's bachelovette

I feel bad that she couldn't take the trip she had planned; and I was a little annoyed with her friend whose car broke down. And honestly; I got very little sleep last night and I'm mainly having trouble thinking about anything that isn't sleeping

A similar thing happened to me where my dad's girlfriend made me miss my cousin's wedding due to a lack of communication. And my dad took her side saying weddings weren't that important; which really frustrates me because my dad chose not to go to my sister's wedding and that's something unforgivable to me; so hearing this story brought me right back to that time.
overly empathic i suppose
I feel bad that this happened to her; as well as empathetic since I can relate to the situation; since I grew up with a car that broke down all the time.
I can understand in a way how the person must have felt because similar issues with car problems have troubled myself in the past as well
surprised about how sad the story in the letter was; anxious feeling is unrelated to the letter but about an upcoming project presentation

This girl clearly had a friend who didn't do the things they were supposed to.  I've had experience with friends like this; so I feel sympathetic for the girl but also frustrated as it makes me remember instances that my friends have let me down.  Lastly I feel stress because being in a situation like that would stress me out.
I think she should have booked the flight in the first place. I would have never trusted someone'e car that was in the shop to drive me to new york city from ann arbor.

It is interesting that I read a letter about a frustrating incident; just as I had wrote about a series of frustrating incidents that happened to me. This person's letter includes frustration towards a person rather than situations like me; but I can still empathize nonetheless.
The writer of the letter had a long story; but ended with a negative experience.

I feel sad and sympathetic for this girl because she missed her best friend's wedding due to a defective part of a car; and missing this wedding seemed to crush her. I also feel a little bit of anger because of the new part being defective. Whether it was the fault of the repair shop worker or not; it angers me that they used a defective part and did not make sure that it would work beforehand.

When I first started reading the letter; the participant made it sound like what they were about to tell me was more sad than it was (like someone died or something). While the participant was clearly upset about their experience and I would be too if it happened to me; I couldn't help but be slightly amused at the fact that in the grand scheme of things; this experience that they were so upset about seems slightly trivial to me.
I feel a bit of sadness; but not entirely.
It's frustrating that her friend lied to her about fixing the car; resulting in her missing her best friend's bachelorette party.

I can relate to the story - looking forward to an experience that means a lot; depending on someone else to assist with making the plans happening; and then being let down because someone I trusted didn't keep their end of the deal.  I'm also wondering if Melissa is still friends with the person who let her down.
I can understand where she's coming from; and it must've sucked.  But at the same time; the way she wrote it is in a very casual manner and it almost makes the story less emotional.
I felt bad for the person that wrote the letter. Especially when they mentioned that they cried. I imagined myself in that situation and how that would feel. I was mad at the world.
She just missed her best friend's bachelorette party. I would feel bad that I did this to my friend and also annoyed that my friend wasn't responsible enough to fix his car .
somebody lied to her and that made her miss a party. I would feel awful and I'm sympathetic being angry at that friend and disappointed that she couldn't make it.

I feel really sorry for Melissa because she couldn't go on the road trip. I also feel really upset that her friend blatantly lied to her and might have even put their lives in danger; had the car broken down in a dangerous situation.
Although it's unfortunate that Melissa missed her friend's bachelorette party; her story seems like something that could be made into a comedy movie. Her troubles were mildly amusing.

Reading about being stranded on the highway is stressful. Also; reading about missing a trip to New York and a party with all of your friends makes me feel stressed and left out. Being lied to makes me angry.

mainfeel3: Wish I could make it better for her
mainfeelexpl: I feel really bad she missed out on that experience; because of how close she is with her friend. You only (usually0 have one bachelorette party.
This is terrible. I feel so bad for the girl. I also know what it is like to miss an important event; not as big as the one she missed; but I can relate to her feelings when she wrote this.
I feel bad for the person who wrote the letter due to her condition but found it funny how she started off the letter by saying she is suppose to be saying something interesting for this project.

The participant missed her best friend's bachelorette party due to a car breaking down on the way to NYC. At the point of writing this letter; she was still upset. It is so unfortunate; especially she really wanted to go and tried her best.
I imagined what the writer may have felt during this experience; and I'm trying to empathize with her. If that were me; I would've been so upset; but also pissed.  That circumstance would suck.

I identify with this person's negative experience. So often; when we are asked to tell stories; we feel like we need to tell the positive ones. But sometimes the negative; less encouraging ones are the ones that need to be told.
While I felt sorry for the writer's misfortune their story was also rather amusing and well told.  As for alert i think that's mainly because I'm taking a study and taking it seriously.
I feel bad that she missed her friends party when it was completely out of her control.

Given the situation she was in; I feel badly for the girl considering that she missed her best friend of 10 years bachelorette party--that really sucks. For some reason though; despite my ability to usually get sucked into emotional readings/movies/television shows; my emotions for her situation weren't that strong. I think it may have to do with the way she wrote the letter. For some reason; despite the anger she claimed to have; it didn't seem that heated to me.

The author put a lot of time into planning the bachelorette party for her best friend and was not able to go because of others failing her. I feel bad that she did everything in her power to plan the event and make it work; but she couldn't control other people's stupid decisions. I hope that she remains optimistic and sees the positives in the situation; but I have a good feeling she is missing those and focusing on the negatives. I also am concerned for the grudges she is holding against the people who wronged her. Though she is justified; I hope she will find peace with the situation and get excited for the wedding and realize that her best friend chose her as the Maid of Honor.
I felt somewhat annoyed because it's only a bachelorette party; yes it was her best friend's; but they can go to NYC another time for a more intimate girls weekend
I wish I could hear this letter writer's sad story in person so I could try to make them feel better or something. But I'm not supposed to get too involved; so I'm not sure how to react.
I can relate to the writer and her experiences. I have experienced disappointment before.

I felt sad and frustrated that the person who wrote this (Melissa) had such an upsetting experience not being able to get to her best friend's bachelorette party and frustrated for what she went through. I am surprised that she chose to write about it; because it was really depressing to read. I just wrote a happy letter so I wasn't expected to read something so sad.
In the letter Melissa missed her friends bachelorette party that she planned just because of car troubles and that's really frustrating and also relatable for me

This girl planned an entire bachelorette party for her friend in NYC and then she was driving there with someone when his car died and they got stranded; so she didn't even get to go to the party. She said she was really upset and I don't blame her at all

mainfeel2: sad for the writer of the letter

mainfeelexpl: I feel really bad for her; I can't imagine having to miss my best friend's bachelorette party that I planned! I can empathize with her because my best friend and I have been best friends for more than 10 years like her and her friend.

I'm sad that she didn't get to go to her best friend's bachelorette party; and am surprised that her friend didn't get his car fixed afterall and lied. I understand where Melissa is coming from in being upset.
I can identify with the participant about trusting somebody and then being disappointed when the person I trusted failed to live up to my trust

I feel sorry for this girl's experience; though I just find it interesting that she would be so upset about something that really wasn't someone else's fault. But; I wasn't there; and I would be upset if I missed my friend's bachelor party too; so I'm still sympathetic.

I feel slightly anxious; like I should be making sure that all of my personal affairs are in order so as to not make the same mistake as the previous participant. I sympathize with her as well given that a very special occasion was unintentionally ruined for her by someone else.

I'm a little confused about the circumstances of the letter.  How did this person expect to plan a bachelorette party in New York when she is in Ann Arbor?  I was also a bit confused about the identities of the people as almost everyone was referred to as "friend".  That said; it is really unfortunate that this person missed an important event in their friends life.  I wonder if it has changed the relationship between this friend and the friend who is getting married.

Well; I am so disappointed this girl could not go to New York! I am sad the car had to break down and upset that after all her planning she could not attend her friend's bachelorette party; especially because she is the maid of honor!

The letter was about a girl who was planning her friend's bachelorrete party in New York; but missed the party due to car troubles. I feel sorry for the author; because she seemed to be very close to her friend and now missed one of the most important days in her friend's life that she actually planned. I also feel sad for the driver; another one of the author's friends; who promised he would take the author to NYC and now probably feels responsible because his car broke down. I feel entertained because it was very well written and I could sympathize with the author.

I fell bad that she didnt get to go on her trip and her friends should not have lied to her. Maybe if she would have planned ahead better she could have given the friend more time to fix his car; but that doesnt really change the fact the he lied which is wrong.

I feel like I'm always slightly stressed all the the time just becuase I remember how much work that I have to do for my jobs and classes. Because of the letter; I felt futuristic in the sense of being excited for the future becuase Melissa wrote about a friend's wedding and another friend's conflict. This made me think of how I went to a friend's wedding last summer and it was so fun - I can't wait to plan my own wedding and go to other people's weddings.
I feel nothing particular other than is was an unfortunate turn of events. I can understand her disappontment.  / i can relate to her frustration
It sucks that the defective car part would have shut down early in the car trip without any signs of trouble before. I wonder if they sent a complaint to the mechanic; as well.
It wasnt the friends fault that the car broke down or that there were no more flights; they were simply bad circumstances that led to a saddening outcome.

I am sad for her situation. Missing your best friends bachelorette party would stink. Frustrated for her reliance on her friend to take her because it did not work out. Sympathetic because things like this inevitably happen to many people and life is hard.

I am both happy and relieved that he or she was able to recover his or her phone; but I am curious as to how his or her zipper opened and I would like to know more about the drive and activities he or she did while on his or her trip.

mainfeel1: Its a bummer that she missed the party
mainfeel2: She needs to improve her communication with her soon to be married friend.
mainfeel3: That was dishonest of her friend to not fix his car

It seems like the person who wrote the letter was really disappointed about the situation and I can understand why. I feel bad that this happened to the participant.

This participant seemed to have been excited about the bachelorette party; but she couldn't because of someone else's mistake

mainfeel2: as if the worst things happen to the most well-intentioned people
mainfeel3: laughing at how thinks work out sometimes

I feel bad that she missed her friend's bachelorette party; it is really sad. I'm also pissed at the boy that said his car was fine.

I am sad because the girl missed her best friend of 10 years bachelorette party and because I felt the emotion while I read it. She said that she was tearing up thinking back on it. I'm interested because I'm not the only one who dreams of going to New York. Lastly; I am kind of upset that her friends car broke down after all the work they did to make sure it was working for the trip.
I feel kind of bad that the person was not able to go to her own bachelorette party for her friend.
The girl described missing her best friend' s bachelorette party because of car troubles; and I feel sympathy for her.
I understand the previous subject's point of view on her experience. It is not something that has made me feel any differently about anything; but I can sympathize with her point of view.

the participant missed her best friend's bachelorete party; and she tried everything she could and even got stuck in the middle of nowhere trying to get there. feel bad for her; and sorry that all her effort went to waste
I feel like; even though it was not directly my fault that I could not go; I am still somewhat to blame because it was my decision to put my faith in my friend who's car broke down.
After reading the letter I feel upset for the writer and I can understand her feelings of disappointment and frustration towards her friend who betrayed her and let her down.
I feel sympathetic towards the writer due to her recent experience that was rather unfortunate. I feel astonished because it was an event that I have only seen in movies or have read about.

I feel upset that Melissa was not able to go to her best friend's bachelorette party and can feel hr disappointment about being unable to go. I feel anger towards the friend (because they had said it was going to be alright) and anger towards the car for breaking down.
